General specifications:

When “cluster” is on: It’s to create a “robust variance matrix”. Sort of corrects inter-temporal correlation, right?

When I lagged covariate, I use a different data set. I made sure this one was right.

These models are mostly Cox Proportional Hazard Models (to predict “when” income taxation was imposed, conditional on covariates).

For the “Recurrent Events” model: COX PH models predict one thing. RE predict the joint appearance of two (or more things) - essentially, multiple failure-time events. In my case, my theory says, basically, “no taxation without representation”. So I predict the jointly appearance of DEMOCRACY and INCOME taxation (and it worked!). These models are called “Andersen-Gill Models”.

Many people, including J. Box-Steffensmeier, recommend to “transform” variables (in log scale) to account for time dynamics. Splines are also recommended, but I didn’t try this. Other transformation are possible within the “time transformed” (tt) argument. “A time-transform term allows variables to vary dynamically in time”. That sounds as a non-linear/flexible transformation?

Besides COX PH I tried “Logit Generalized Estimating Equations” (tax=1, no tax = 0). “The GEE logit estimates the same model as the standard logit regression. Unlike in logit regression, GEE logit allows for dependence within clusters, such as in longitudinal data”.

I also tried “conditional logits”, these are the homologous to “fixed effects logit” models.

# Here below are the models

## Model with "time-transformed" variables
cox1.tt = coxph(Surv(year, incometax.s) ~ tt(constmanufact) + tt(constagricult) + cluster(country), 
                data=cox, x=T
)

##  Model with logged independent variables
cox2 = coxph(Surv(year, incometax.s) ~ log(constmanufact) + log(constagricult) + log(totpop) + cluster(country), 
             data=cox
)


## Another possible transformation is to lag the independent variables
### Here I use a data set that is lagged.
cox.L = coxph(Surv(year, incometax.s) ~ log(constmanufact.L) + log(constagricult.L) + log(totpop) + cluster(country), 
              data=L.cox)


## Logit Generalized Estimating Equations
logitgee.1 = zelig(incometax.d ~ ln.constmanufact + ln.constagricult + ln.totpop, 
                   model = "logit.gee", 
                   id = "country", 
                   cite = FALSE,
                   data = logitgee)


# Multiple Failures: Income Tax AND Democracy
## Here the panel ends when both democracy AND income tax appear. Both events are "1". So each panel has two 1s.
cox2.ag = coxph(Surv(year, dem.tax) ~ log(constmanufact) + log(constagricult) + log(urbpop) + cluster(country), 
                data=ag.data
)


# Conditional Logit (FE model)
clogit.1 = clogit(incometax.d ~  log(constmanufact) + log(constagricult) +strata(country), method= "efron", data = data)

Now, lets try some post estimations

COX PH assume that the haxards, are, “proportional”. Lets see if this assumption is “correct”

## Testing Prop. Assumption
test.assumption = cox.zph(cox2, transform = 'log')
print(test.assumption)
##                        rho    chisq     p
## log(constmanufact)  0.0213 0.000706 0.979
## log(constagricult) -0.0409 0.003579 0.952
## log(totpop)         0.0987 0.021272 0.884
## GLOBAL                  NA 0.347609 0.951
plot(test.assumption[1]) # Industry

plot(test.assumption[2]) # Agriculture

If the proportional hazards assumption is true, beta(t) will be a horizontal line. The printout gives a test for slope=0. A p-value less than 0.05 indicates a violation of the proportionality assumption. Safe to say the assumption holds

We can also simulate quantities of interest.

# Load the libraries
## devtools::install_github('christophergandrud/simPH')
library(simPH)

# I use non-logged covariates for simulation (since it seems that the sim function doesn't take well natural logs)
cox3 = coxph(Surv(year, incometax.s) ~ constmanufact + constagricult + totpop + cluster(country), 
             data=cox
)

# Show the table.
stargazer(cox3,
          type = "text", # change to "latex"/"text" when nedded
          #covariate.labels=c("Agr/Ind Proportion"),
          dep.var.labels=c("Income Taxation"),
          label = "results:1",
          notes = "Robust Std. Errors in Parentheses",
          title = "Structural Origins of Income Taxation",
          font.size = "scriptsize",
          table.placement = "h",
          notes.align = "c",
          style = "apsr")

# Simulate the RELATIVE HAZARD for a sequence that goes from MIN to the MAX of the Industrial Output
sim3.m <- coxsimLinear(cox3, 
                       b = "constmanufact", 
                       qi = "Relative Hazard",
                       Xj = seq(min(cox$constmanufact), max(cox$constmanufact), by=250)
                       )
## All Xl set to 0.
## 15703 (62.8%) simulations dropped for having
## quantity of interest values: Inf/NA/NaN/>1000000.
## 
## To keep extreme values set extremesDrop = FALSE.
# Simulate the RELATIVE HAZARD for a sequence that goes from MIN to the MAX of the Agricultural Output
sim3.a <- coxsimLinear(cox3, 
                       b = "constagricult", 
                       qi = "Relative Hazard",
                       Xj = seq(min(cox$constagricult), max(cox$constagricult), by=150)
                       )
## All Xl set to 0.
# It says "All Xl set to 0" b/c it sets the reference category to 0.
# Hazard ratios are COMPARISONS, so the coefficients mean the effects of the Betas, relative to 0.

# Plot
## IMPORTANT! A relative hazard for a unit at zero is always one, as it is a ratio of the hazards with itself. Gandrud2015 p. 10
simGG(sim3.m, xlab = "Industrial Output", ylab="Relative Hazard of Income Taxation")

simGG(sim3.a, xlab = "Agricultural Output", ylab="Relative Hazard of Income Taxation")
